The '''PWP Catch Division Championship''' is a [[professional wrestling]] [[Championship (professional wrestling)|championship]] owned by [[Pro Wrestling Pride]]. It was the first championship incorporated by Pro Wrestling Pride, and the company's second-tier championship behind the [[PWP Heavyweight Championship]]. Despite the championship being the secondary championship for the promotion, it has been known to main-event shows above the heavyweight championship. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=155026|title=PWP << Events Database << Cagematch|first=Philip|last=Kreikenbolm|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>

The championship was established on the first Pro Wrestling Pride show under the company's banner on 13 May 2012, where Tyler Hawke defeated Wales' 'Wild Boar' Mike Hitchman. The design of the championship is that of a [[trophy]] rather than a traditional [[championship belt]]. Despite the championship being predominately male, it has been won by a female. Bobbi Tyler won the championship for a single day in January 2017.

==Catch Division Wrestling==
Rather than a midcard title based on a weight (Such as [[All Japan Pro Wrestling]]'s [[World Junior Heavyweight Championship (AJPW)| Junior Heavyweight Championship]], or [[World Championship Wrestling]]'s [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991–2007)| Cruiserweight championship]]), and is more in line with [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]]'s [[X-Division]] Championship, which stated the division was 'not about weight limits, it's about no limits!"<ref name="slam-dvdreview">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Reviews/2006/12/23/2950856.html|title=No limits to second X Division DVD|last=McNamara|first=Andy|publisher=Slam! Sports|accessdate=10 June 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108010440/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Reviews/2006/12/23/2950856.html|archivedate=8 January 2015|df=}}</ref> The catch division, was likely originally designed as a showcase of [[catch wrestling]], rather than high-flying wrestling, with well known grapplers [[Johnny Kidd (wrestler)|Johnny Kidd]] and [[Doug Williams (wrestler)|Doug Williams]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://callingspots.com/profiles/doug-williams/|title=Doug Williams - Calling Spots|publisher=Calling Spots|accessdate=11 October 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013173734/http://callingspots.com/profiles/doug-williams/|archivedate=13 October 2017|df=}}</ref> winning the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=2511|title=Pro Wrestling Pride Catch Division Championship « Titles Database « Cagematch - The Internet Wrestling Database|first=Philip|last=Kreikenbohm|publisher=}}</ref>

However, the style has changed over the duration of the belt's life, with the aforementioned catch style, with a mix of luchador, [[Puroresu]] and even more 'extreme styles'. This is reflected in the match types contested for this championship, with "catch as catch can" wrestling style (See [[Admiral-Lord Mountevans rules| Mountevans Rules]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=1542421|title=Johnny Kidd's last Devon Stand « Titles Database « Cagematch - The Internet Wrestling Database|first=Philip|last=Kreikenbohm|publisher=}}</ref>, [[Lucha libre#Luchas de Apuestas| Luchas de Apuestas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlingpride.com/torquay-saturday-17th-may/tyler-hawke-vs-ultimo-tiger-press-confrence|title=Tyler Hawke vs. Ultimo Tiger Press Confrence|first=Dyer|last=Edward|publisher=Pro Wrestling Pride|date=19 April 2014|accessdate=11 October 2017}}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=Lee Vilenski |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and even [[Tables, Ladders, and Chairs match| TLC]] matches. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=161934|title=PWP Undisputed 2 « Titles Database « CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|first=Philip|last=Kreikenbohm|publisher=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320102833/https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=161934|archivedate=20 March 2018|df=}}</ref> The division's prize was a catch division trophy, and not a traditional belt. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlingpride.com/roster.html|title=Pro Wrestling Pride Roster|publisher=Pro Wrestling Pride|first=Edward|last=Dyer|accessdate=9 October 2017|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810032816/http://www.prowrestlingpride.com/roster.html|archivedate=10 August 2017|df=}}</ref>

